Let $\mathsf {Ret}$ be the event that the output is not ⊥. Then, \begin{align*} &\frac{1}{(1+\varepsilon)|sol({\varphi })|} \le \Pr [ \sigma \text{ is output} \mid \mathsf {Ret}] \le \frac{1+\varepsilon }{|sol({\varphi })|} \\ &\text{ For some constant } c,\ \Pr [\mathsf {Ret}] > c \end{align*}



The problem of almost-uniform generation was first considered by Jerrum, Valiant, and Vazirani [10] who showed that almost-uniform generation can be achieved in probabilistic polynomial time given access to an approximate counter, which in turn employs a $\mathsf {SAT}$ oracle. In particular, the JVV algorithm makes $\mathcal {O}(n^2\log n + n\log n\log \varepsilon ^{-1}))$ calls to a SAT oracle (defined formally in Section 2) and uses 2-wise independent hash functions. The work of Jerrum et al. also considered the stricter notion of uniform generation (wherein ɛ = 0) and showed that uniform generation can be accomplished in probabilistic polynomial time given access to $\Sigma _2^P$ oracle. Subsequently, Bellare, Goldreich, and Petrank [2] showed that uniform generation can be achieved in probabilistic polynomial time given access to $\mathsf {NP}$ oracle. In particular, their proposed procedure, henceforth referred to as $\mathsf {BGP }$, makes $\mathcal {O}(n^2\log n)$ calls to $\mathsf {SAT}$ oracle but requires n − wise independent hash functions. One can express t − wise independent hash functions with polynomial of degree t over GF(2n). The high degree of polynomials make computations over them expensive and therefore, one would ideally like to work with polynomials of as small degree as possible. Therefore, from theoretical perspective, one wonders whether we can design algorithmic procedure for almost-uniform generation that makes fewer queries to $\mathsf {SAT}$ oracle and requires hash functions with smaller independence. The need for efficient algorithms is exacerbated by the wide ranging applications of uniform sampling in diverse domains such as pathogen transmission inference in bioinformatics [17], constrained-random simulation for bug discovery for software and hardware [15], probabilistic inference for graphical models [5], and the like. In all such applications, the practical implementation of uniform generators replace $\mathsf {SAT}$ oracle with a state of the art SAT solver. Therefore, one would ideally like to make as fewer calls to a $\mathsf {SAT}$ oracle (a SAT solver in practice) as possible and use hash functions with as small independence as possible. 1.1 Our Results The key contribution of this work is to establish the following two theorems: Theorem 1.1 Given access to $\mathsf {SAT}$ oracle, for all ɛ > 0, there exists a probabilistic polynomial time almost-uniform generation procedure for Boolean Formulas that makes $\mathcal {O}(\varepsilon ^{-1} + \log n \cdot \log \varepsilon ^{-1})$ queries to $\mathsf {SAT}$ oracle and uses 3 − wise independent hashing. If given access to only 2 − wise independent hash family, we obtain the following: Theorem 1.2 Given access to $\mathsf {SAT}$ oracle, for all ɛ > 1 , there exists a probabilistic polynomial time almost-uniform generation procedure for Boolean Formulas that makes $\mathcal {O}(\log n \cdot \log \left(\frac{1}{\varepsilon -1}\right))$ queries to $\mathsf {SAT}$ oracle and uses 2 − wise independent hashing. To put our results in the context of existing work, we summarize our results along with existing results in Table 1. Table 1: Almost-uniform generators along with the number of queries and the independence of hash functions where n = |X| $\mathsf {SAT}$ Queries Indep. Notes BGP [2] $\mathcal {O}(n^2 \log n)$ n ɛ = 0 CMV [8] $\mathcal {O}(\frac{1}{(\varepsilon -1.71)^{2}} + \log n)$ 3 ɛ > 1.71 JVV [10] $\mathcal {O}(n^2 \log n + n \log n \log \varepsilon ^{-1})$ 2 ɛ > 0 Theorem 1.1 $\mathcal {O}(\varepsilon ^{-1} + \log n\cdot \log \varepsilon ^{-1})$ 3 ɛ > 0 Theorem 1.2 $\mathcal {O}(\log n\cdot \log (\frac{1}{\varepsilon -1}))$ 2 ɛ > 1 In typical use cases of uniform sampling, ɛ is set to a small constant. Therefore, from practical perspective, for a fixed ɛ, we improve the complexity of almost-uniform generation from $\mathcal {O}(n^2\log n)$ to $\mathcal {O}(\log n)$ while requiring 3 − wise independence instead of 2 − wise independence. It is worth noting that the standard construction of t − wise independent hash function is a random t − 1 degree polynomial in a large enough prime field. But thankfully, for small constant independence, more efficient constructions are known. In particular, the tabulation-based hashing dating back to Carter and Wegman [4] is known to be 3 − wise (and hence, 2-wise) independent [12]. Formally, a random hash function belonging to tabulation-based hashing h: {0, 1}n↦{0, 1}m can be constructed as h(X) = AX + b where A is a m × n matrix while b is m × 1 0-1 vector and each entry of A and b is either 0 or 1 with equal probability (i.e., 1/2). Tabulation-based scheme is shown to be significantly faster than alternative construction using degree 2-polynomials [16]. The availability of hash functions that can be described using linear function over GF(2) plays a consequential role in practical implementation of the techniques. It is worth emphasizing that we consider a salient strength of this paper is the simplicity of the algorithm including usage of simple data structures. Furthermore, the associated analysis takes a different route in comparison to prior work [2, 8, 10]. In particular, in our view, we offer a much simpler and intuitive analysis methodology in comparison to prior work. Another important contribution of our work is a nuanced complexity analysis, presented in Section 6, that seeks to capture both time and space complexity of SAT queries; such an analysis is inspired from the practical behavior of SAT solvers. To illustrate the practical impact of improvement due to our results, we implemented the three samplers wherein we employed the state of the art SAT solver, $\mathsf {CryptoMiniSAT}$, to perform SAT calls. Our empirical evaluation over 562 benchmarks show that while our algorithm can successfully sample within one hour for all such instances, JVV timed out on 544 out of 562 instances . The rest of the paper is organized as follows: In Section 2, we introduce the basic notations and preliminaries. In Section 3, we present background overview of inner workings of JVV and BGP to put our contribution in context. We present the primary technical contribution of this paper in Section 4. In Section 5, we discuss how our proposed scheme can be extended to handle arbitrary $\mathsf {NP}$ relations. In Section 7, we provide empirical evidence to demonstrate that the theoretical improvements lead to significant improvements in practice. We finally conclude in Section 8.

2 PRELIMINARIES In this section, we will state basic notations and preliminaries. 2.1 Boolean Formulas Let φ denote a Boolean formula in conjunctive normal form (CNF), and let X be the set of variables appearing in φ. Let n = |X|. A satisfying assignment or witness of φ is an assignment that makes φ evaluate to true. We denote the set of all witnesses of φ by sol(φ). $\mathsf {SAT}$ Oracle In this work, we assume access to a $\mathsf {SAT}$ oracle that takes in a formula φ and returns a satisfying assignment σ if φ is satisfiable and ⊥ is φ is unsatisfiable. The model of $\mathsf {SAT}$ oracle captures the behavior of the modern SAT solvers. Since the problem of satisfiability is self-reducible, one can easily show that the our model of $\mathsf {SAT}$ oracle can be linearly (in n) simulated via the model of $\mathsf {NP}$ decision oracle, which returns Yes or No. $\mathsf {BSAT}$ Procedure In this work, we use the gadget of $\mathsf {BSAT}$, which was introduced by Bellare et al in [2]. Formally, given a formula φ and threshold t, $\mathsf {BSAT}$ returns a set of solutions W such that |W| = min(t, |sol(φ)|). The following proposition characterizes the complexity of $\mathsf {BSAT}$. Proposition 1. $\mathsf {BSAT}$ can be implemented in polynomial time given access to a $\mathsf {SAT}$ oracle and makes $\mathcal {O}(t)$ calls to $\mathsf {SAT}$ oracle. Proof. The following procedure suffices: □ 2.2 Approximate Model Counting A problem closely related to almost-uniform generation is that of approximate model counting. Given a CNF formula φ, a tolerance θ > 0 and a confidence parameter δ ∈ (0, 1], a probabilistic approximate model counter ${\mathsf {ApproxCount}}(\cdot, \cdot, \cdot)$ ensures that \begin{align*} \mathsf {Pr}[\frac{|sol(\varphi)|}{1+\theta } \le {\mathsf {ApproxCount}}(\varphi, \theta, \delta) \le (1+\theta)|sol(\varphi)|] \\ \ge 1-\delta. \end{align*}

We will employ $\mathsf {ApproxCount}$ as a gadget and the following theorem establishes the runtime complexity. Proposition 2. [3, 21] Given a CNF formula φ over n variables, tolerance θ > 0 and a confidence parameter δ ∈ (0, 1], there exists a probabilistic approximate model counter that runs in probabilistic polynomial time given access to a $\mathsf {SAT}$ oracle and makes $\mathcal {O} (\log (n/\theta) \log (1/\delta))$ calls to $\mathsf {SAT}$ oracle. Proof. We will use the procedure $\mathsf {ApproxMC}$ as a subroutine; the following claim captures the complexity of $\mathsf {ApproxMC}$ as stated in Theorem 4 of [9]:□ Claim 1 Given a CNF formula φ over n variables, tolerance $\hat{\theta } > 0$ and a confidence parameter δ ∈ (0, 1], $\mathsf {ApproxMC}$ runs in probabilistic polynomial time given access to a $\mathsf {SAT}$ oracle and makes $\mathcal {O} (\log (n) \cdot \frac{1}{\hat{\theta }^2} \cdot \log (1/\delta))$ calls to $\mathsf {SAT}$ oracle, and returns an estimate c such that \begin{align*} \Pr \left[ \frac{|sol({\varphi })|}{1+\hat{\theta }} \le c \le (1+\hat{\theta }) |sol({\varphi })| \right] \ge 1-\delta \end{align*}

Given a formula φ over n variables. We first construct another formula ψ such that ψ is essentially t copies of φ where $t > \frac{1}{\log (1+\theta)}$. Formally, let φ be defined on the set of variables X(1) such that n = |X(1)|. We now create another (t − 1) sets of fresh variables, denoted by X(2), …X(t), such that each of these sets have n variables. Formally, |X(1)| = |X(2)| = …|X(t)| = n. We can now define ψ as follows: \begin{align*} \psi := \varphi (X^{(1)}) \wedge \varphi (X^{(1)} \mapsto X^{(2)}) \cdots & \wedge \varphi (X^{(1)} \mapsto X^{(t)}) \end{align*}

Where X(1)↦X(i) means that we substitute the variables of the set X(1) by the variables of the set X(i) in the formula. Note that |sol(ψ)| = |sol(φ)|t. Next, we compute an estimate $\mathrm{initEst} = \mathsf {ApproxMC}(\psi, 1, \delta)$. Now our estimate of the |sol(φ)| is simply (initEst)1/t. Note that the number of calls to SAT oracle is $\mathcal {O} (\log (n/\hat{\theta }) \log (1/\delta))$. It is probably worth emphasizing that the trick of creating multiple copies is fairly standard, and is indeed used in Figure 1 of [3] as well. 2.3 k-wise Independent Hashing Let and $\mathcal {H}(n,m) \subseteq \lbrace h:\lbrace 0,1\rbrace ^{n} \rightarrow \lbrace 0,1\rbrace ^m \rbrace$ be a family of hash functions mapping {0, 1}n to {0, 1}m. We use $h \xleftarrow {R} \mathcal {H}(n,m)$ to denote the probability space obtained by choosing a function h uniformly at random from $\mathcal {H}(n,m)$. Definition 1 A family of hash functions $\mathcal {H}(n,m)$ is k − wise independent if for all distinct y 1 , y 2 , ⋅⋅⋅y k ∈ {0, 1}n and $\forall \alpha _1, \alpha _2, \cdots \alpha _k \in \lbrace 0,1\rbrace ^m, h \xleftarrow {R} \mathcal {H}(n,m)$, \begin{align*} \mathsf {Pr}[(h(y_1) = \alpha _1) \wedge \cdots \wedge (h(y_k) = \alpha _k)] = \left(\frac{1}{2^{m}}\right)^k \end{align*}

We are interested in the set of elements of sol(φ) mapped to cell α by h, denoted $\mathsf {Cell}_{\langle \varphi, h, \alpha \rangle }$ and its cardinality. Formally, $\mathsf {Cell}_{\langle \varphi, h, \alpha \rangle }= \lbrace y \mid y \in sol({\varphi }) \text{ and } h(y) = \alpha \rbrace$. In our work, we will be interested in a fixed α and for simplicity, we will fix α = 0. We will use shorthand ${\mathsf {Cnt}_{\langle \varphi, h \rangle }}$ to denote $|\mathsf {Cell}_{\langle \varphi, h, \mathbf {0} \rangle }|$. Typically, higher the value of k, stronger one can obtain concentration bounds on the random variable ${\mathsf {Cnt}_{\langle \varphi, h \rangle }}$. In particular, the concentration bounds of the following form are typically obtain: \begin{align*} \Pr \big [ \left| \mathsf {Cnt}_{\langle \varphi, h \rangle }- \mathsf {E}[ \mathsf {Cnt}_{\langle \varphi, h \rangle }] \right| \ge \beta \mathsf {E}[\mathsf {Cnt}_{\langle \varphi, h \rangle } \big ] \\ \le f(\mathsf {E}[ |\mathsf {Cnt}_{\langle \varphi, h \rangle }], k, \beta) \end{align*}

The standard concentration bounds lead to $f(\mathsf {E}[ |\mathsf {Cnt}_{\langle \varphi, h \rangle }|],$ k, β) such that f is monotonically decreasing in $k, \beta, \mathsf {E}[ |\mathsf {Cnt}_{\langle \varphi, h \rangle }|]$. The following proposition concerning 2-wise and 3-wise hash functions is important in our analysis Proposition 3. Given a 2-wise independent hash family H(n, m), for $h \xleftarrow {R} H(n,m), \forall \sigma \in sol({\varphi }), \forall \alpha \in \lbrace 0,1\rbrace ^m$ $\mathsf {E}[\mathsf {Cnt}_{\langle \varphi, h \rangle } ]=\frac{|sol({\varphi })|}{2^m}$

$\mathsf {E}\left[\mathsf {Cnt}_{\langle \varphi, h \rangle } \bigm \vert h(\sigma)=\mathbf {0}\right]=1 +\frac{|sol({\varphi })|-1}{2^m}$

$Var \left[\mathsf {Cnt}_{\langle \varphi, h \rangle }\right]=\frac{|sol({\varphi })|}{2^m}-\frac{|sol({\varphi })|}{2^{2m}}\le \mathsf {E}[\mathsf {Cnt}_{\langle \varphi, h \rangle }]$

If H(n, m) is also a 3-wise independent hash family, then $Var[ \mathsf {Cnt}_{\langle \varphi, h \rangle } \mid h(\sigma)=\alpha ]=\frac{|sol({\varphi })|-1}{2^m}-\frac{|sol({\varphi })|-1}{2^{2m}}\le \mathsf {E}[\mathsf {Cnt}_{\langle \varphi, h \rangle } \mid h(\sigma)=\mathbf {0}]$

Proof. ∀ω ∈ sol(φ), let γ ω, α be the indicator variable of the event h(ω) = α. \begin{align*} \gamma _{\omega,\alpha } = {\left\lbrace \begin{array}{@{}l@{\quad }l@{}}1 & \text{if } h(\omega)=\alpha \\ 0 & \text{otherwise} \end{array}\right.} \end{align*}

Since $\mathsf {Cnt}_{\langle \varphi, h \rangle }=\sum _{\omega \in sol({\varphi })} \gamma _{\omega,\alpha }$, therefore, \begin{align*} \mathsf {E}[\mathsf {Cnt}_{\langle \varphi, h \rangle }] = \sum _{\omega \in sol({\varphi })} \mathsf {E}[\gamma _{\omega,\alpha }] &= \sum _{\omega \in sol({\varphi })} \Pr [h(\omega) = \alpha ]\\ & = \frac{|sol({\varphi })|}{2^m} \end{align*}

Given h(σ) = α, we have γ σ, α = 1. Therefore, \begin{align*} \mathsf {E}[\mathsf {Cnt}_{\langle \varphi, h \rangle } \mid h(\sigma)=\alpha ]=1 +\frac{|sol({\varphi })|-1}{2^m} \end{align*}

The variance is $Var[ \mathsf {Cnt}_{\langle \varphi, h \rangle } ] = \sum _{\omega \in sol({\varphi })}Var[ \gamma _{\omega,\alpha } ] + \sum _{\omega

