5 UNIVERSAL GENERATORS So far we have focused on one particular $\mathsf {NP}$ relation: SAT but the core framework can be applied to any arbitrary $\mathsf {NP}$ relation with minor modifications. To this end, we will first fix some notations: given an $\mathsf {NP}$ language L, let R be the NP-relation defining L, i.e. L = {y | ∃w such that R(y, w) = 1}. Also, let n = |y|, and without loss of generality, we can assume $R_{y}\stackrel{def}{=} \lbrace x\ |\ R(y,x)=1\rbrace \subseteq \lbrace 0,1\rbrace ^n$. Similar to [2], for h: {0, 1}n↦{0, 1}m, y ∈ L R , we can define \begin{align*} R_{y,h} = \lbrace w \in R_{y} \mid h(w) = 0 \rbrace = h^{-1}(0) \cap R_{y} \end{align*}

The following proposition generalizes the Proposition 1 Proposition 5. [2] For every $\mathsf {NP}$ relation R, there is a polynomial time oracle algorithm $\mathcal {M}_1$ that takes in y ∈ L R , h ∈ H(n, m), and $\mathsf {thresh}$ as input and outputs R y, h if $|R_{y,h}| \le \mathsf {thresh}$ and ⊥ otherwise. $\mathcal {M}_1$ makes $\mathcal {O}(n\cdot \mathsf {thresh})$ calls to $\mathsf {NP}$ oracle. Proof. Let consider the set S R, h = {(y, k) | ∃z 1 , z 2 ...z k such that z 1 ...z k are distinct and ∀i ∈ [1, k], R(y, z k ) = 1 and h(z k ) = 0} and $S_{R,h}^{\prime }=\lbrace (y,k,i,j)\ | \ \ \exists z_1\prec z_2\prec...\prec z_k \mathrm{\ such\ that\ } z_{i,j}=1 \mathrm{\ and\ } \forall l\in [1,k],R(y,z_l)=1\mathrm{\ and\ } h(z_l)=0 \rbrace$ Here, z i, j is the j-th bit of z i and ≺ denotes some ordering relation. As R is an NP relation and h can be computed in polynomial time, these sets are in NP. Then, given the access to a NP oracle, $\mathcal {M}_1$ can be implemented as follow. It is immediate that we make at most $1 + \mathsf {thresh}+ \mathsf {thresh}\cdot n \in \mathcal {O}(n\cdot \mathsf {thresh})$ calls to the oracle.□ Note that when m = 0, h is just an identity function, and therefore, we will omit mentioning h for the special case when m = 0. We also have an analogous generalization for Proposition 2. Proposition 6. [3] For every $\mathsf {NP}$ relation R, there is a probabilistic polynomial time algorithm $\mathcal {M}_2$ that takes in y ∈ L R , θ > 0, and δ > 0 as input and returns an estimate ν such that \begin{align*} \Pr \left[ \frac{|R_{y}|}{1+\theta } \le

u \le (1+\theta) |R_{y}| \right] \ge 1-\delta \end{align*}

$\mathcal {M}_2$ makes $\mathcal {O}(\log (n/\theta) \log (1/\delta))$ calls to $\mathsf {NP}$ oracle. Furthermore,makescalls tooracle. Equipped with the two propositions, we can now finally state the theorem: Theorem 5.1 Let R be an $\mathsf {NP}$-relation. Then there exists an almost-uniform generation procedure for R for all ɛ > 0 that makes $\mathcal {O}(n\varepsilon ^{-1})$ queries to $\mathsf {NP}$ oracle and uses 3 − wise independent hashing. Proof. Given proposition 5 and 6 we can adapt our algorithm by replacing BSAT by $\mathcal {M}_1$ and ApproxCount by $\mathcal {M}_2$. We state the pseudocode of the algorithm in Algorithm 3 for completeness. Then, it is immediate that our algorithm makes $\mathcal {O}(n\varepsilon ^{-1} + \log n \log (\varepsilon ^{-1})) \in \mathcal {O}(n\varepsilon ^{-1})$ queries to the NP oracle.□

